I not quite sure what you want to achieve when you call `.map` on the `Result`.

There are two edge cases defined in the swift `Result` enum type:

* Either it is of type `.success&lt;Success&gt;`
* or it is of type `.failure&lt;Failure&gt;`

Taking a look into your `init` extension of `Result`:

    public extension Result {
        init(_ success: Success?, _ failure: Failure?) {
            if let success = success {
                self = .success(success)
            } else if let failure = failure {
                self = .failure(failure)
            } else {
                fatalError(&quot;Illegal combination found.\n Success: \(success as Any), Failure: \(failure as Any)&quot;)
            }
        }
    }

I can see that if the first parameter (`snapshot` in your case) is non-`nil`, you create a `.success` Result, else you create a `.failure` Result with the provided `error`. If both are `nil`, you crash with a `fatalError`

When you call `.map` on the `Result`, this will internally only be executed if the `Result` is `.success`, e.g. the `snapshot` is non-`nil`. Yet, in your map closure, you check if `snapshot.exists` and, if not, you return `nil`. But this will be illegal, because it would lead to a new `Result.success` with a `nil` associated value.

You have to check the logic of how you want the `.success` result be mapped to a new result type. 

I guess what you _really_ want is the following: If there is a `snapshot`, _and_ `snapshot.exits` is true, then you want to call the completion handler with `Result.success`, else with `Result.failure`. Something _similar_ to this:

    T.subCollectionRef(of: parentDocument.ref).document(documentID).getDocument { snapshot, error in
        if let snapshot = snapshot, snapshot.exists {
          completion(Result.success(snapshot))
        } else {
          Result.failure(error)
        }
    }

