The `Switch` widget use the adaptative mode, and if you check the source code, you will find something like this:

```
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    switch (widget._switchType) {
      case _SwitchType.material:
        return buildMaterialSwitch(context);

      case _SwitchType.adaptive: {
        final ThemeData theme = Theme.of(context);
        assert(theme.platform != null);
        switch (theme.platform) {
          case TargetPlatform.android:
          case TargetPlatform.fuchsia:
            return buildMaterialSwitch(context);
          case TargetPlatform.iOS:
            return buildCupertinoSwitch(context);
        }
      }
    }
    assert(false);
    return null;
  }
}
```

It will use the `buildMaterialSwitch` method for `Android` and `buildCupertinoSwitch` for iOS.

Checking the `buildCupertinoSwitch` method:

```
  Widget buildCupertinoSwitch(BuildContext context) {
    final Size size = getSwitchSize(Theme.of(context));
    return Container(
      width: size.width,  // Same size as the Material switch.
      height: size.height,
      alignment: Alignment.center,
      child: CupertinoSwitch(
        dragStartBehavior: widget.dragStartBehavior,
        value: widget.value,
        onChanged: widget.onChanged,
        activeColor: widget.activeColor,
      ),
    );
  }
```

That&#39;s the key, then you have to use `CupertinoSwitch` widget :), just don&#39;t forget to add the import:

```
import &#39;package:flutter/cupertino.dart&#39;;
```

